## Mathematical content

- A literal is either a propositional variable `P` or the negation `\neg P` of a propositional variable.
- A positive literal is a literal of the form `P`.
- A negative literal is a literal of the form `\neg P`.
- Complementary literals are `P` and `\neg P` for the same propositional variable.
- A clause is a finite disjunction of literals.
- A term is a finite conjunction of literals. It may also be called a conjunction term.
- The empty clause is the empty disjunction and is read semantically as false.
- The empty conjunction is read semantically as true.

